english:
  title: The Rustic of Geumnam
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A Confucian scholar named Master Damun lived in Geumnam. One day, a rustic from Geumnam, having never heard the name of a learned man, came seeking an audience with the master. He said to the master's servant: "I am but a rustic, humble and unlearned. Yet I have heard that those who dwell above and govern the state are called ministers and nobles, those below who till the fields are called farmers, those who fashion implements are called craftsmen, and those who trade in goods are called merchants. But never have I heard of something called a 'scholar.' One day the people of my village spoke excitedly, saying 'A scholar comes! A scholar comes!'—meaning the Master here. What work does he do that people call him a scholar?"

    The servant replied: "What the Master cultivates extends far and wide. His learning encompasses heaven and earth itself. He observes the transformations of yin and yang, the disposition of the five elements, the shining of sun, moon, and stars, and he examines the heights of mountains and the flows of rivers and seas, the flourishing and withering of grasses and trees—thereby understanding the nature of spirits and the mysteries of the visible and invisible worlds.

    "In clarifying human relationships, he understands that between ruler and subject there is righteousness, between father and son there is affection, between husband and wife there is distinction, and among the young, the elder, and friends there is order and trust. He cultivates reverence, affection, discernment, and integrity in all these bonds.

    "In comprehending the ages from past to present, from the very beginning of written language to this day, he grasps the rise and fall of the world's order, the beauty and ugliness of customs, the enlightenment and darkness of rulers, the treachery and loyalty of ministers, the rightness and wrongness of words and deeds, the origins and corruptions of ritual and music and law and governance, the coming and going of the worthy and the virtuous—understanding the true direction toward which all things tend.

    "He knows that human nature derives from Heaven's command, that the four moral sprouts and five constants and all principles of ten thousand things are woven together within this nature—this is not the emptiness of the Buddhists. He knows that the Way flows from the simple conduct of daily human life and encompasses the vast forms of heaven and earth—this is not the nothingness of the Daoists. Thus he distinguishes the harmful false teachings of Buddha and Laozi, opening the eyes of the blind across a hundred generations. He counters the shallow pursuit of profit in the current age, guiding people back to the true Way of righteousness.

    "Should a ruler employ him, peace settles both above and below. Should his students follow him, their virtue flourishes and their endeavors prosper. Should he remain unrecognized by his times, he leaves his teachings in writing for those yet to come. And his faithfulness is such that he would rather face the world's censure than betray the teachings of the sages; rather starve and stumble through hardship than commit what is unjust, for his heart would be forever shamed. This is the work of a scholar, and this is what the Master seeks to accomplish."

    The rustic then said: "How grandiose these words! Is this not mere exaggeration? I have heard from the elders of my village: 'When a name exists without substance, spirits despise it. Even when substance exists, if one displays it openly, one incurs the anger of men.' Thus, when a man presents himself as virtuous, others will not honor him; when he boasts of his wisdom, others will not aid him. For this reason the gentleman is cautious in such matters. Since you follow the Master in his wanderings and speak thus with such grand claims, I can well imagine the Master's nature. If he does not earn the hatred of spirits, he will surely earn the anger of men. Alas! The Master is in grave peril. I have no wish to see him—I fear his misfortune might reach me as well."

    With that, he swept his sleeve and departed.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This work is a philosophical dialogue that critiques excessive display of virtue and knowledge. It reflects Jung Do-jeon's (1342-1398) engagement with Neo-Confucian thought during the early Joseon period.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four moral sprouts' (四端) refer to compassion, shame, respect, and the discernment of right and wrong. The 'five constants' (五典) refer to the five Confucian virtues and relationships.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast with Buddhism (emptiness/無) and Daoism (non-action/無) underscores the Neo-Confucian assertion that virtue operates within concrete human relationships and the natural order, not through transcendence or withdrawal.
